{"query": "What key factors are associated with the success or failure of amphibian colonization and breeding in newly created ponds?", "summary": "Based on the action documents, several key factors are associated with amphibian colonization and breeding success in newly created ponds. Pond age affects use and colonization, with one study finding that survival of translocated Oregon spotted frogs increased with increasing age of created ponds (Action 865). Distance to existing ponds is a critical factor, as use or colonization of created ponds was affected by distance to existing ponds (Action 869), and numbers of species in restored wetlands were affected by proximity to source ponds (Action 879). The surrounding landscape and habitat context influences success, with colonization affected by surrounding landscape (Action 869) and numbers of amphibian species and abundance affected by surrounding habitat (Action 880).

Water permanence is important, with studies finding that colonization was affected by pond permanence (Action 869), and that numbers of species were similar or lower depending on the permanence of created water bodies (Action 869). Vegetation cover influences success, as use or colonization was affected by vegetation cover (Action 869), and amphibian abundance in created wetlands was affected by vegetation (Action 880). Fish presence is a major factor affecting breeding success, with amphibian abundance affected by fish presence (Action 880), and studies showing that draining ponds to eliminate fish increased numbers of amphibian species (Action 826) and increased breeding success of frog or newt species (Action 826).

Pond design characteristics influence colonization, with amphibian abundance in created wetlands affected by wetland design (Action 880). Water levels are significant, as amphibian abundance was affected by water levels (Action 880), and maintaining pond water levels enabled successful breeding (Action 833). Overall colonization rates vary significantly, with studies showing amphibians used 64-100% and reproduced in 64-68% of created ponds, or used 8-100% and reproduced in 2-62% depending on species (Action 869).", "action_ids": ["869","865","879","880","826","833"]}

